# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1897-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1891-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1891 throughout the world.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] The **1891 Washington Statesmen** baseball team finished the season with a 44–91 record in the American Association in their first season.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] After the season, the AA disbanded and the Washington club, renamed the "Senators," joined the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The **1892 Washington Senators season** was a season in American professional baseball.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The team, which had played in the now-defunct American Association in 1891 as the **Washington Statesmen**, was purchased by J.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Earl Wagner and moved to the National League for the 1892 season.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] In a split season schedule, the Senators finished seventh in the first half of the season and last in the second half.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Overall, the team had a record of 58–93, 10th-best in the 12-team National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The Senators held spring training in Savannah, Georgia at Bolton Street Park.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1893-washington-senators-season] The **1893 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 40–89 record, last place in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1894-washington-senators-season] The **1894 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 45–87 record, eleventh place in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1895-washington-senators-season] The **1895 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 43–85 record, tenth place in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1896-washington-senators-season] The **1896 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 58–73 record, tied for ninth place in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1897-washington-senators-season] The **1897 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 61–71 record, tied for sixth place in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1897-washington-senators-season] The Senators (also known as the Nationals) finished in the first division in the only time in the franchise's nine-year run in the National League.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1897-washington-senators-season] After getting off to a dismal 31–55 start, Washington won 30 of its last 46 games.
[src:1897-washington-senators-season/1897-washington-senators-season] Their overall winning percentage (.462) would be the high-water mark for this franchise before it folded in contraction at the conclusion of the 1899 season.
